The '''2003 Atlantic hurricane season''' was an active [[Atlantic hurricane|Atlantic]] [[List of Atlantic hurricane seasons|hurricane season]] with [[tropical cyclone|tropical activity]] before and after the official bounds of the season – the first such occurrence in 50&nbsp;years. The season produced 21&nbsp;[[tropical cyclone]]s, of which 16&nbsp;developed into named storms; seven cyclones attained hurricane status, of which three reached [[tropical cyclone scales|major hurricane status]]. With sixteen storms, the season was tied for the sixth most active [[List of Atlantic hurricane seasons|Atlantic hurricane season]] on record. The strongest hurricane of the season was [[Hurricane Isabel]], which reached [[List of Category 5 Atlantic hurricanes|Category 5]] status on the [[Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale]] northeast of the [[Lesser Antilles]]; Isabel later struck [[North Carolina]] as a Category&nbsp;2 hurricane, causing $3.6&nbsp;billion in damage (2003&nbsp;[[USD]], $4.04&nbsp;billion 2007&nbsp;USD) and a total of 51&nbsp;deaths across the Mid-Atlantic region of the United States.

The season began with [[Tropical Storm Ana (2003)|Subtropical Storm Ana]] on [[April 20]], prior to the official start of the season; the bounds of the season are from [[June 1]] to [[November 30]], which conventionally delimit the period of each year when most tropical cyclones form in the Atlantic basin. In early September, [[Hurricane Fabian]] struck [[Bermuda]] as a [[Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale|Category 3]] hurricane, where it was the worst hurricane since [[1926 Atlantic hurricane season|1926]]; on the island it caused four deaths and $300&nbsp;million in damage (2003&nbsp;USD, $336&nbsp;million 2007&nbsp;USD). [[Hurricane Juan]] caused considerable destruction to [[Nova Scotia]], particularly [[Halifax Regional Municipality, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], as a Category&nbsp;2 hurricane, the first hurricane of significant strength to hit the province since [[1893 Atlantic hurricane season|1893]]. Additionally, Hurricanes [[Hurricane Claudette (2003)|Claudette]] and [[Hurricane Erika (2003)|Erika]] struck [[Texas]] and [[Tamaulipas]], respectively, as minimal hurricanes.

